{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568108"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19483"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.21,0.61,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1790"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 80-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of progressive peripheral vision loss. The visual loss was initially mild but has progressed to interfere with his daily activities. He reports an accompanying headache that has progressively worsened and is now associated with nausea and vomiting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals bitemporal hemianopia. Ophthalmoscopy shows papilloedema. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal. An MRI scan is performed (Image) which reveals a large craniopharyngioma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What additional complication is most likely to present in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellar ataxia","Anosmia","Hypopituitarism","Facial nerve palsy","Seizures"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a craniopharyngioma, which is a benign tumour arising from embryonic remnants of Rathke\u0027s pouch. Due to its location in the suprasellar region, it commonly affects both the optic chiasm (causing bitemporal hemianopia) and the pituitary gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypopituitarism\u003C/strong\u003E is a common and significant complication of craniopharyngioma, occurring in up to 85% of patients. The mass can compress or destroy the pituitary gland and stalk, leading to deficiencies in multiple hormones including growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, and gonadotropins. This requires careful endocrine evaluation and hormone replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellar ataxia\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely as the cerebellum is not anatomically related to the suprasellar region where craniopharyngiomas typically occur. Ataxia would be more commonly associated with posterior fossa tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnosmia\u003C/strong\u003E (loss of smell) is typically associated with anterior cranial fossa lesions affecting the olfactory nerves. Craniopharyngiomas in the suprasellar region do not typically affect the sense of smell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacial nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual as the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) travels through the posterior cranial fossa and is anatomically distant from the typical location of craniopharyngiomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeizures\u003C/strong\u003E, while possible with any intracranial mass, are less common with craniopharyngiomas compared to tumours involving the cerebral cortex. The suprasellar location makes seizures a less likely complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Craniopharyngioma classically presents with bitemporal hemianopia due to compression of the optic chiasm.","Progressive headache with nausea and vomiting suggests raised intracranial pressure.","Hypopituitarism is a common complication of craniopharyngioma due to compression or destruction of the pituitary gland."],"references":["M\u00fcller HL. Craniopharyngioma. Endocr Rev. 2014;35(3):513-543. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/edrv/article/35/3/513/2354694","M\u00fcller HL, Merchant TE, Warmuth-Metz M, Martinez-Barbera JP. Craniopharyngioma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019;5(1):75. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-019-0116-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18597"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20532"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18597"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media